Query: What challenge is observed in real retrieval when instructions are applied?  
Layman: When instructions are added to search queries, similar results often stay at the top of the list, making it hard to tell if the model truly understands the instructions or is just matching keywords and meanings it already knows.  

Blog: &lt; One common challenge in real-world search systems is that when special instructions are added to a query, the results don’t change much. This happens because the system may already be returning strong matches based on keywords and meaning alone. As a result, it's difficult to know whether improvements in results come from the model actually understanding the new instructions or just from its existing ability to match similar content. This makes testing true instruction understanding a big challenge. &gt;  
Forum: &lt; A major issue in real retrieval is that when you add instructions to a search, the top results often stay the same. This makes it hard to judge if the model is really following the instructions or just relying on keyword and meaning matches it already knows well. &gt;

An arrow \( f : x \to y \) in an ∞-category with pullbacks is exponentiable if it satisfies any of the following equivalent conditions:  
(1) the pullback functor \( f^* : C/y \to C/x \) admits a right adjoint;  
(2) \( f \) is exponentiable when viewed as an object in \( C/y \);  
(3) for every arrow \( g : a \to y \), the functor \( (f^*g)^* : C/a \to C/(a \times_y x) \) admits a right adjoint.
